Chapbooks Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Chapbook

Chapbooks were small, inexpensive pamphlets popular in Europe and America from the 16th century until the mid-19th century. They contained of a variety of reading material, including folklore, reports of crimes, ballads, and Bible stories, and reveal much about popular culture at the time. Sold by itinerant agents known as "chapmen" for as little as a penny, they were typically unsigned, undated, and flimsy. After they were read, they were often put to use in what other ways? More... Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Chapbook Discuss Link: https://forum.thefreedictionary.com/postst201213_Chapbooks.aspx

Samantha Smith Visits the Soviet Union (1983) Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Samantha+Smith

In 1982, Samantha Smith, a 10-year-old American girl, wrote a letter to the newly elected leader of the USSR, Yuri Andropov, asking if he intended to start a war. Andropov replied personally. Expressing a desire for lasting peace with the US, he invited Smith to visit. The following July, she and her parents spent two weeks in the USSR amidst a media frenzy that hailed her as a goodwill ambassador. After her death in a plane crash two years later, she was honored by both nations in what ways? More... Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Samantha+Smith Discuss Link: https://forum.thefreedictionary.com/postst201214_Samantha-Smith-Visits-the-Soviet-Union--1983-.aspx

Gustav Mahler (1860) Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Mahler,+Gustav

Mahler was an Austrian composer and conductor. After studying in Vienna, he conducted at numerous prominent opera houses where his high standards became legendary, but his refusal to compromise aroused intense personal opposition. He composed in his free time, mostly during the summer, and completed nine symphonies in his lifetime. The biggest success of his career—the 1910 premiere of his eighth symphony—was overshadowed by Mahler's discovery of his wife's affair with what famous architect? More... Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Mahler,+Gustav Discuss Link: https://forum.thefreedictionary.com/postst201215_Gustav-Mahler--1860-.aspx

Today's Holiday

? Link: /_/help/help2.htm#2211210
Background: remove this box from homepage

Calgary Stampede Link: //encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Calgary+Exhibition+and+Stampede

The 10-day Calgary Stampede Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Calgary+Stampede is Canada's largest rodeo event, offering a world-class rodeo competition in saddle bronc and bareback riding, steer wrestling, calf roping, and bull riding, as well as a chuck wagon race that carries a $175,000 prize. Most of the rodeo events are held in the 130-acre Stampede Park in downtown Calgary Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Calgary , but there's also a Wild West town called Weadickville (named for Guy Weadick Link: //encyclopedia.thefreedictionary.com/Guy+Weadick , who founded the event in 1912), an Indian Village populated by representatives of five Indian tribes from the nearby Plains, a Frontier Casino, and agricultural and livestock exhibits. More... Link: //encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Calgary+Exhibition+and+Stampede Discuss Link: https://forum.thefreedictionary.com/postst201216_Calgary-Stampede.aspx
